article.headline: Stanford 71, Dartmouth 54
article.story: STANFORD, Calif. (AP) -- Chris Hernandez has been spending some extra time in the gym lately and it's beginning to pay off. Dan Grunfeld scored 15 points and Hernandez added 14 to help Stanford win its 17th straight home game, 71-54 over Dartmouth on Wednesday night. "I've been getting to practice early and putting up a lot of shots," Hernandez said. "We have different people in different roles this year and there are different points of emphasis." Hernandez hit two quick 3-pointers to jump start the Cardinal offense in the second half and Stanford rolled to its third straight win. "We haven't had a solid win like this all year," Hernandez said. "It was pretty nice." David Gardner scored 11 points to lead Dartmouth (3-6), which lost its third straight. The Big Green lost in double overtime to UC Davis on Monday night. "We just didn't show enough energy here," Dartmouth coach Terry Dunn said. "Stanford came in confident. Playing at home will do that for you, plus they beat the team we lost to." Stanford has won 26 of its last 27 home contests, while the Big Green remained winless in four road games. The teams have met just six times, and this was the first since the 1971-72 season. Stanford has won five of the meetings, including in the 1942 NCAA championship game -- the Cardinal's lone men's basketball national title. The Big Green made their first trip to the West Coast in five years, and played their first game against a Pac-10 team in 12 years. Dartmouth fell to 3-15 against the Pac-10. Stanford improved to 24-8 against the Ivy League. The Cardinal haven't lost to an Ivy League school since the 1981-82 season. Hernandez's long-range shooting helped Stanford open a 16-point edge in the first five minutes of the second half. Dartmouth's leading scorer Mike Lang was forced to leave the game midway through the second half after getting hit in the head with the basketball as he scrambled for a loose ball. He returned later. Grunfeld scored eight of his 10 first-half points during a 10-0 run as Stanford opened a 25-14 lead with 6:04 remaining. Stanford never trailed in the game, though the Big Green kept it close through the first half. Reserve Peter Prowitt, a 6-foot-10 freshman forward, blocked four shots as the Cardinal took a 33-24 advantage into intermission.
